\item{A clipboard}{
  \p{
    As a ~mathematician, you want to always have something at hand to write on. This thing needs to be big enough that you don't get cramped, have a hard back so you don't have to put it down on a surface (i.e if you're in an auditorium without a table), and you need to avoid running out of pages.
  }
  \p{
    The traditional solution to this is a notebook of some kind. But these have a finite number of pages, so you need to be getting new ones constantly. The actual cost of this is probably pretty minor, but (I've found) the organizational load is pretty substantial, plus I have a tendency to get precious about not "wasting" the pages. The clipboard is inexpensive, and can be refilled infinitely with blank sheets of paper. The only downside is if you're saving your notes, but my experience with such things is that anything not written deliberately to be saved (in which case you can just put the sheet in a folder) is not worth saving anyways.
  }
